A SQL Login (Contained) refers to a user account that is fully contained within a single SQL Server database â€” it does not depend on a server-level login. This type of user is called a contained database user.

ğŸ” What Is a Contained User?
A contained user:

Exists only in the database.

Authenticates directly against the database, not through a server login (syslogins) or Windows account.

Does not require a corresponding login on the SQL Server instance.

This is part of SQL Serverâ€™s Contained Database feature, which helps isolate databases from the SQL Server instance they run on.

âœ… Benefits
Benefit	Description
ğŸ” Easy portability	You can back up and restore the database to another instance without needing to recreate logins.
âŒ No SID mismatch	Avoids issues like orphaned users (User X exists in the database but not in the login list).
ğŸ” Database-level security	All user authentication happens at the database level.

ğŸ“¦ How to Create a Contained User
First, enable contained databases at the server level:

sql
Copy
Edit
EXEC sp_configure 'contained database authentication', 1;
RECONFIGURE;
Then create a contained database user:

sql
Copy
Edit
-- Create a contained user with password
CREATE USER [db_user_name] WITH PASSWORD = 'StrongPassword123!';
-- Grant roles/permissions as needed
ALTER ROLE db_datareader ADD MEMBER [db_user_name];
âš ï¸ Note: You do not use CREATE LOGIN here.

ğŸ”‘ Difference: Contained vs Traditional Users
Feature	Traditional SQL Login	Contained User
Requires server login	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
Authentication scope	Server	Database
Orphaned user risk	âœ… Possible (if login missing)	âŒ Avoided
Portability	âŒ Manual login migration	âœ… Easy backup/restore

ğŸ” Authentication Types
Contained users support:

SQL Authentication (username + password)

Windows Authentication (less common but possible)

ğŸ“Œ Use Cases
Multi-tenant databases

Databases that need to be easily moved between servers

Reducing dependency on DBA management of server-level logins

